0240","display_label":"Brown Memorial Baltimore founding pastor; later Calvary Philadelphia","link_text":"Rev. John Sparhawk Jones"}],"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"career","header":"Pastor Sixth Presbyterian Philadelphia, twenty-three years","body":"Pastor of Sixth Presbyterian Church Philadelphia from 1838 to 1861 — a twenty-three-year tenure at a major Old School Presbyterian congregation. Stepped down 1861 to become Secretary of the Presbyterian Relief Fund for Disabled Ministers, serving in that role until his 1868 death."},{"number":2,"category":"career","header":"Wrote 1849 biography of Ashbel Green","body":"His 1849 'Life of Ashbel Green VDM' became the definitive nineteenth-century treatment of Ashbel Green (1762-1848), eighth president of Princeton 1812-1822 and one of the major figures of early-American Presbyterianism. Joseph's biographical scholarship extended also to editing the 1861 Autobiography of Rev. William Neill, Dickinson College president 1824-1829."},{"number":3,"category":"career","header":"Honorary Doctor of Divinity, Lafayette College, 1843","body":"Received an honorary Doctor of Divinity from Lafayette College 1843 — conferred while his older brother Joel Jones was still a Lafayette trustee. Two Jones brothers thus held Lafayette honors a generation apart: Joel as founding-era board secretary and trustee, Joseph as honorary DD recipient."}],"quotes":[],"sources":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"slug":"joseph-jones-1797"},"TD0256":{"id":"TD0256","former_ids":[],"is_placeholder":false,"has_descendants_documented":false,"bio":{"first_name":"Samuel","middle_name":"Howell","last_name":"Jones","married_names":[],"gender":"male","display_name":"Samuel Howell Jones"},"gender":"male","birth":{"year":1826,"country":"United States"},"baptism":{},"death":{"year":1885,"month":3,"day":9,"city":"Philadelphia","county":"Philadelphia","state":"Pennsylvania","country":"United States"},"residence":{"city":"Philadelphia","county":"Philad